<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-publishing" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Publishing</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      As you develop a book, you may want to make draft output available online
      so readers can give early feedback. After the writing is finished, you may
      also need to think about more formal publishing options such as printed
      copies or e-books.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="rstudio-connect">
    <title>RStudio Connect</title>

    <p>
      The Rmd chapter begins with a simple publishing route: render the book and
      deploy the output. It highlights <c>publish_book()</c> in
      <c>bookdown</c> as a convenience wrapper for publishing to
      <url href="https://bookdown.org" visual="bookdown.org"/>, the hosting
      service described there as being built on top of
      <url href="https://posit.co/products/enterprise/connect/"
      visual="posit.co/products/enterprise/connect/"/>.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>publish_book(name = NULL, ...)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The first time you try to publish, the service asks you to authorize
      <c>bookdown</c> to publish to your account. After that, you can publish
      again without repeating the authorization step. The original instructions
      point readers to <url href="https://bookdown.org/connect/"
      visual="bookdown.org/connect/"/> for the initial sign-in flow.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>bookdown::publish_book(render = 'local')</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter notes that the <c>render</c> argument is the main setting most
      readers may want to change, and that a self-hosted RStudio Connect server
      can be used as an alternative destination.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="netlify-drop">
    <title>Netlify Drop</title>

    <p>
      Netlify Drop is presented as a quick way to publish a static HTML book
      without first placing the project under version control. All you need is a
      local <c>bookdown</c> project that can be built to an output directory.
    </p>

    <subsection xml:id="build-and-deploy-pipeline-sequence">
      <title>The build-and-deploy pipeline sequence</title>

      <p>The chapter describes the flow as:</p>

      <ol>
        <li><p>start with a local <c>bookdown</c> project;</p></li>
        <li><p>build the book locally, usually into <c>_book/</c>;</p></li>
        <li><p>drag the output directory into the Netlify Drop interface;</p></li>
        <li><p>repeat the local build and upload process whenever the book changes.</p></li>
      </ol>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="before-you-begin">
      <title>Before you begin</title>

      <p>
        The project does not need to live on GitHub or in any other
        version-controlled repository. If you need a practice project, see
        <xref ref="fig-new-bs4-book-pretext"/> for how to create a new book in
        RStudio, or use the function <c>bookdown::create_gitbook()</c> or
        <c>bookdown::create_bs4_book()</c> from your R console.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="build-your-book">
      <title>Build your book</title>

      <p>
        Build the book locally using whichever method from
        <xref ref="build-the-book"/> you prefer.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="deploy-your-site">
      <title>Deploy your site</title>

      <p>
        Go to <url href="https://app.netlify.com/drop" visual="netlify.com/drop"/>
        and drop the output directory from your project into the upload area.
        By default this will usually be <c>_book/</c>, unless you changed the
        output directory in <c>_bookdown.yml</c>.
      </p>

      <p>
        The chapter notes that deployment is fast and that Netlify initially
        assigns a random subdomain such as
        <c>https://random-word-12345.netlify.com</c>. Unclaimed sites are deleted
        after 24 hours, but signing up for a Netlify account lets you keep the
        site online permanently.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="optional-update-your-site">
      <title>Optional: Update your site</title>

      <p>
        After signing up for Netlify, you can manually update the site from the
        Deploys page by dragging and dropping the folder again
        (see <xref ref="fig-netlify-drag-drop-pretext"/>).
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-netlify-drag-drop-pretext">
        <title>Screenshot of drag and drop deploy update box on Netlify.</title>
        <image source="images/netlify-drag-drop-update.png" width="100%">
          <description>
            <p>A screenshot of Netlify's drag-and-drop deployment update area.</p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </figure>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="netlify-subdomain">
      <title>Optional: change the default subdomain</title>

      <p>
        The chapter explains how to change the generated Netlify subdomain from
        the site settings page, and points readers to Netlify's custom-domain
        documentation if they want to use their own domain instead.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="drawbacks-and-alternatives">
      <title>Drawbacks and alternatives</title>

      <p>
        This workflow is convenient for quickly sharing a prototype, but it is a
        manual process and does not make much use of version control. For books
        under active collaboration, the chapter recommends more automated,
        repository-based workflows.
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="github">
    <title>GitHub</title>

    <p>
      <url href="https://pages.github.com" visual="pages.github.com"/> can host
      the HTML output of a <c>bookdown</c> project for free. Because the output
      is already a complete static site, the important detail is to add a
      hidden <c>.nojekyll</c> file so GitHub does not try to rebuild the site
      with <url href="http://jekyllrb.com" visual="jekyllrb.com"/>.
    </p>

    <program language="bash">
      <input># assume you have initialized the git repository,
# and are under the directory of the book repository now

# create a hidden file .nojekyll
touch .nojekyll
# add to git here because will not show up in RStudio
git add .nojekyll</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also mentions a <c>/docs</c>-based GitHub Pages workflow on
      the main branch by setting <c>output_dir: "docs"</c> in
      <c>_bookdown.yml</c> and configuring the repository settings accordingly,
      following the linked GitHub Help page at
      <url href="http://bit.ly/2cvloKV" visual="bit.ly/2cvloKV"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another option is to publish from a dedicated <c>gh-pages</c> branch. The
      Rmd source provides these setup commands.
    </p>

    <program language="bash">
      <input># assume you have initialized the git repository,
# and are under the directory of the book repository now

# create a branch named gh-pages and clean up everything
git checkout --orphan gh-pages
git rm -rf .

# create a hidden file .nojekyll
touch .nojekyll
git add .nojekyll

git commit -m"Initial commit"
git push origin gh-pages</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Once that groundwork is done, the rest can be automated in scripts and run
      from the cloud. The chapter uses
      <url href="https://travis-ci.com" visual="travis-ci.com"/> as its main
      example of a server that can rebuild and redeploy the book whenever new
      commits are pushed.
    </p>

    <program language="bash">
      <input># configure your name and email if you have not done so
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
git config --global user.name "Your Name"

# clone the repository to the book-output directory
git clone -b gh-pages \
  https://${GITHUB_PAT}@github.com/${TRAVIS_REPO_SLUG}.git \
  book-output
cd book-output
git rm -rf *
cp -r ../_book/* ./
git add --all *
git commit -m "Update the book"
git push -q origin gh-pages</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>language: r
pandoc_version: 1.19.2.1

env:
  global:
    - secure: A_LONG_ENCRYPTED_STRING

before_script:
  - chmod +x ./_build.sh
  - chmod +x ./_deploy.sh

script:
  - ./_build.sh
  - ./_deploy.sh</input>
    </program>

    <program language="dcf">
      <input>Package: placeholder
Type: Book
Title: Does not matter.
Version: 0.0.1
Imports: bookdown, ggplot2
Remotes: rstudio/bookdown</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>sudo: false

cache:
  packages: yes
  directories:
    - $TRAVIS_BUILD_DIR/_bookdown_files</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The Rmd chapter closes this section by noting that GitHub Pages and Travis
      CI are only examples, not requirements, and that any server capable of
      hosting static output can be used.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="features-for-html-publishing">
    <title>Features for HTML publishing</title>

    <subsection xml:id="html-404">
      <title>HTML 404 pages</title>

      <p>
        For HTML books, <c>bookdown</c> creates a custom <c>404.html</c> page in
        the output directory (see <xref ref="fig-404-page-pretext"/>). Hosting
        platforms such as Netlify, GitHub Pages, and GitLab Pages can use this
        file as the site's custom not-found page.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-404-page-pretext">
        <title>Screenshot of an example 404 page.</title>
        <image source="images/404.png" width="100%">
          <description>
            <p>A screenshot of the example 404 page embedded within a rendered HTML book.</p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The chapter explains that the 404 page remains embedded within the book
        layout so readers can still use the overall navigation and styling. To
        customize it, add either <c>_404.Rmd</c> or <c>_404.md</c> to the project
        root. If a root-level <c>404.html</c> file already exists,
        <c>bookdown</c> leaves it untouched.
      </p>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="metadata-for-sharing">
      <title>Metadata for sharing</title>

      <p>
        HTML books can also expose metadata for social sharing on platforms such
        as Twitter, Facebook, and LinkedIn. The key inputs come from the
        <c>index.Rmd</c> YAML, especially the book <c>url</c>, the
        <c>cover-image</c>, the <c>title</c>, and the <c>description</c>.
      </p>

      <figure xml:id="fig-social-og-pretext">
        <title>Sharing preview on Facebook and LinkedIn.</title>
        <image source="images/social-og.png" width="100%">
          <description>
            <p>A screenshot of the social-sharing card preview shown on Facebook and LinkedIn.</p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <figure xml:id="fig-social-twitter-pretext">
        <title>Sharing preview on Twitter.</title>
        <image source="images/social-twitter.png" width="100%">
          <description>
            <p>A screenshot of the social-sharing card preview shown on Twitter.</p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </figure>

      <p>
        The chapter recommends validating this metadata with
        <url href="https://www.opengraph.xyz" visual="opengraph.xyz"/> or with
        platform-specific tools for Facebook, LinkedIn, and Twitter.
      </p>
    </subsection>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="publishers">
    <title>Publishers</title>

    <p>
      Beyond online publishing, the chapter discusses working with a traditional
      publisher or self-publishing. It emphasizes that publishers who support
      LaTeX make it much easier to publish a book written with <c>bookdown</c>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The book's example uses the Chapman &amp; Hall/CRC class
      <c>krantz.cls</c>, but the same general approach also applies to other
      publisher classes such as Springer's <c>svmono.cls</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>documentclass: krantz
lot: yes
lof: yes
fontsize: 12pt
monofont: "Source Code Pro"
monofontoptions: "Scale=0.7"</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      In the LaTeX preamble (see <xref ref="yaml-options"/>), the Rmd source
      shows a set of tweaks for fonts, floating environments, quotations, and
      hyperlink handling.
    </p>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\setmainfont[
  UprightFeatures={SmallCapsFont=AlegreyaSC-Regular}
]{Alegreya}</input>
    </program>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\renewcommand{\textfraction}{0.05}
\renewcommand{\topfraction}{0.8}
\renewcommand{\bottomfraction}{0.8}
\renewcommand{\floatpagefraction}{0.75}</input>
    </program>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\renewenvironment{quote}{\begin{VF}}{\end{VF}}</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The quote environment style can be seen in <xref ref="markdown-syntax"/>.
    </p>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\let\oldhref\href
\renewcommand{\href}[2]{#2\footnote{\url{#1}}}</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>bookdown::pdf_book:
  includes:
    in_header: latex/preamble.tex
    before_body: latex/before_body.tex
    after_body: latex/after_body.tex
  keep_tex: yes
  dev: "cairo_pdf"
  latex_engine: xelatex
  citation_package: natbib
  template: null
  pandoc_args: --top-level-division=chapter
  toc_unnumbered: no
  toc_appendix: yes
  quote_footer: ["\\VA{", "}{}"]
  highlight_bw: yes</input>
    </program>

    <program language="latex">
      <input>\frontmatter
\mainmatter</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter explains why <c>cairo_pdf</c> is used to embed fonts, why
      <c>highlight_bw</c> is useful for black-and-white printing, and why
      <c>xelatex</c> was chosen to simplify custom-font support. The index is
      printed via <c>latex/after_body.tex</c> as described in
      <xref ref="latex-index"/>.
    </p>
  </section>
</chapter>
